    "109073200061238502007/02/07 02:02:09HeathcliffIf you don't plan on getting any rare alchemy recipes, then transmutation mastery is the one to do.\
\
Look at it this way... assuming everyone can make a potion, then its price should vary with the price of the herbs on the AH. The same thing happens with the enchantments people can learn from NPCs. No one can craft any better than anyone else; no one can do it cheaper. If you have a mastery in potions then you can make the potion for slightly cheaper.. Assuming one in 4 potions gives you 1 extra, then you're producing at 80% the cost. However, if two people can produce at 80% the cost, then they're basically just competing with each other to see who is more comfortable making less money. However if you're one of a few with an alchemy recipe, then you're only competing with those people... and if you're the only one of those with potion spec, then if they are ALWAYS selling at 0% markup on their potions, you can ALWAYS afford to make 20% profit selling at their price... or make 15% profit and sell for slightly below theirs (so yours will always sell first).\
\
Transmutes are different, however. Since they're on cooldown, you the market's supply is limited by the number of alchemists.\
\
Ideally your guild should have one of each spec and the rest transmutes; and have your potion and elixir specs in on every raid. This way when either a potion or elixir recipe drops it isn't \"wasted\" on a person who can't proc on it (and your guild won't miss out on that 1 extra every 4).",
