    "1025316764npcNitrin the Learned19844npcRamdor the Mad1941717450The Sha'tar500110227210228310231410251510252610253",
    "10253112730511067272007/06/29 07:04:38skywyzeI, too,  have soloed Levixus as a hunter (67 at the time). However, it is NOT as easy as some would have you believe. The only advice I can give that the others didn't mention before is the following:\
\
1. Have your pet on auto-growl and manually set it to attack every infernal as they're summoned. AoE effects like Thunderstomp and Screech are not good enough - you need your pet to growl to get sufficient aggro.\
2. Lay down frost traps (NOT freezing traps) every chance you get. Since Levixus himself is immune to slowing/freezing effects, he'll start walking way ahead of his infernals, thus buying you time.\
3. Do a Mend Pet every time you do a Call Pet. It'll need that health.\
4. Keep aspect of the pack/cheetah on at all times. \
5. Make sure you know where the camp is and what the shortest route to it is. I accidentally dragged Levixus into the middle of the wrong camp, dragging him way farther than I actually had to.\
6. Don't worry about doing damage. Save your mana for Mend Pet and trapping.\
7. Once you get to the camp and the guards start beating up Levixus, lay down the smack. I unleashed hell and still didn't get aggro over the guards. And even if I had, I could just have feigned death.\
\
Congratulations if you can accomplish this. Especially if you weren't 70 at the time. It's a remarkably interesting encounter in that it tests the skill of the player, rather than the character. I dare say that even an epicced out level 70 character couldn't solo Levixus in a flat face-to-face encounter. You have to use your wits to win. So if you manage, be proud. You've earned it.",
